<subSubSection pageId="9" pageNumber="314" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="9.[151,1437,150,465]" pageId="9" pageNumber="314">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,345,222,248]" pageId="9" pageNumber="314">Distribution</emphasis>
: Native to south and southeast Asia including 
<collectingCountry box="[868,928,223,249]" name="India" pageId="9" pageNumber="314">India</collectingCountry>
, southwestern 
<collectingCountry box="[1095,1165,223,249]" name="China" pageId="9" pageNumber="314">China</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[1176,1310,223,249]" name="Hong Kong" pageId="9" pageNumber="314">Hong Kong</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[1321,1432,223,249]" name="Myanmar" pageId="9" pageNumber="314">Myanmar</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[151,253,259,285]" name="Thailand" pageId="9" pageNumber="314">Thailand</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[268,325,259,285]" name="Laos" pageId="9" pageNumber="314">Laos</collectingCountry>
, and 
<collectingCountry box="[391,486,259,285]" name="Vietnam" pageId="9" pageNumber="314">Vietnam</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Archer, M. E." box="[504,654,258,285]" pageId="9" pageNumber="314" pagination="47 - 53" refId="ref6210" refString="Archer, M. E. (1995) Taxonomy, distribution and nesting biology of the Vespa mandarinia group (Hym., Vespinae). The Entomologist's Monthly Magazine, 131, 47 - 53." type="journal article" year="1995">Archer 1995</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Smith-Pardo, A. H. &amp; Carpenter, J. M. &amp; Kimsey, L." box="[669,952,259,285]" pageId="9" pageNumber="314" pagination="1 - 27" refId="ref7923" refString="Smith-Pardo, A. H., Carpenter, J. M. &amp; Kimsey, L. (2020) The diversity of hornets in the genus Vespa (Hymenoptera: Vespidae; Vespinae), their importance and interceptions in the United States. Insect Systematics and Diversity, 4, 1 - 27. https: // doi. org / 10.1093 / isd / ixaa 006" type="journal article" year="2020">
Smith-Pardo 
<emphasis box="[821,881,259,285]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="314">et al.</emphasis>
2020
</bibRefCitation>
), adventive in northwest Nearctic (Kozak 2020).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="9" pageNumber="314" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="9.[151,1437,150,465]" pageId="9" pageNumber="314">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,314,330,356]" pageId="9" pageNumber="314">Diagnosis</emphasis>
: 
<taxonomicName box="[331,465,331,356]" class="Insecta" family="Vespidae" genus="Vespa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="314" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="soror">
<emphasis box="[331,465,331,356]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="314">Vespa soror</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be distinguished from other 
<taxonomicName box="[842,997,331,357]" pageId="9" pageNumber="314">
<emphasis box="[842,907,331,356]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="314">Vespa</emphasis>
species
</taxonomicName>
that have been recorded in 
<collectingCountry box="[1316,1400,331,357]" name="Canada" pageId="9" pageNumber="314">Canada</collectingCountry>
by having a combination of the following characters: 1) gena length at least 1.7× the length of eye (
<figureCitation box="[1233,1321,366,393]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="8.[151,250,1943,1967]" captionTargetBox="[225,1362,181,1920]" captionTargetId="figure-22@8.[225,1362,181,1920]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURE 5. Vespa soror specimen collected at Vancouver, British Columbia, Canada. A. Dorsal habitus. B. Lateral habitus. C. Anterior view of head. Vertical arrow in C shows the distance between posterior ocellus and posterior edge of vertex; horizontal arrow shows distance between posterior ocellus and eye. Scale bars: 1 mm." pageId="9" pageNumber="314">Fig. 5B</figureCitation>
), 2) metasomal tergum 1 length at least half of posterior width, and 3) terga 3–6 black (
<figureCitation box="[1040,1129,402,429]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="8.[151,250,1943,1967]" captionTargetBox="[225,1362,181,1920]" captionTargetId="figure-22@8.[225,1362,181,1920]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURE 5. Vespa soror specimen collected at Vancouver, British Columbia, Canada. A. Dorsal habitus. B. Lateral habitus. C. Anterior view of head. Vertical arrow in C shows the distance between posterior ocellus and posterior edge of vertex; horizontal arrow shows distance between posterior ocellus and eye. Scale bars: 1 mm." pageId="9" pageNumber="314">Fig. 5B</figureCitation>
), sometimes with a narrow posterior band of orange on tergite 3.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
